<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>UKPHR</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from UK Public Health Register (HCP0007)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key Issues</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Health and Care Professions Council (HCPC) regulates a large and diverse range of professionals and practitioners</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">With regard to public health, current government proposals are that the HCPC takes responsibility for the regulation of one part of the public health workforce, the multidisciplinary Public Health Specialists.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The lack of engagement of the HCPC with existing regulators has raised concerns over the capacity of the HCPC to deliver a comparable regulatory system to ensure consistence of regulation across the entire public health profession including Medical and Dental Public Health Consultants</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK Public Health Register (UKPHR) was set up at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arms</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> length from Government in 2003 to manage a voluntary register of public health specialists. It was intended to provide a regulatory home for those specialists who are neither doctors nor dentists (and therefore not already statutorily regulated by the General Medical Council and the General Dental Council). In this way, an accredited, multi-disciplinary professional leadership has since developed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Through the work of the UKPHR with partner organisations, it has become a condition of recruitment for the most senior posts that an applicant must be registered by UKPHR or the General Medical Council or the General Dental Council. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The multi-disciplinary nature of UKPHR’s registrants (over 500 today) is demonstrated in the range of professional backgrounds, including environmental health, health protection, nursing and pharmacy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Statutory or voluntary regulation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The previous Government invited Gabriel </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, a Regional Director of Public Health, to review</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the regulatory arrangements for the multi-disciplinary public health specialists. In 2010 he reported to the current Government on a range of options, including continuation of voluntary regulation, statutory regulation by UKPHR and statutory regulation by another regulator. A further option (regulation of all public health specialists by the General Medical Council) was not viable because the General Medical Council felt unable to extend its role. Dr </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> recommended statutory regulation in place of voluntary, took cognizance of the Government’s policy in relation to the burden of regulation, thereby rejected the option of converting UKPHR into a statutory regulator and recommended that the multi-disciplinary public health specialists who are not doctors or dentists should be regulated by HCPC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR is a voluntary regulator but is willing to be the statutory regulator for some or all the public health workforce if this should become public policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Former Secretary of State, the Rt Hon Andrew </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lansley</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> MP, announced in January 2012 that the Government intended to implement this recommendation. Currently, we are all waiting for the Department of Health to publish a Consultation Paper. The Consultation Paper had been expected to be published in July 2013, but currently, the earliest publication date is said by the Department to be March 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Development of public health workforce</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In April 2013 the Department of Health published England’s new </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Public Health Workforce Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. There are 14 commitments for strengthening the public health workforce and supporting its development. Of particular interest are the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (known as the Public Health Skills and Careers Framework until its refresh during 2013), the proposal for a public health workforce </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">skills passport</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the arrangements for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">regulation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of this workforce.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since 2011, UKPHR has piloted voluntary registration of public health practitioners in England, Wales and Scotland in addition to its regulation of public health specialists.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is intended that registration of practitioners will offer employers the same assurance of professional competence as for specialists. The practitioner workforce is much larger than the specialist cadre and together, the public health specialists and practitioners represent a significant public health community of practice whose actions and decisions can affect population health for a long period of time. To ensure that there is equality in competency across the entire public health workforce the UKPHR is:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.77pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raising the visibility of this important workforce </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.77pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raising awareness of the critical outcomes of improving people’s health and reducing health inequalities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.77pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensuring there is consistency in the competency and standards of practice across the entire profession</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public safety</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The purpose of registration is, first and foremost, to protect the public and promote public confidence in public health practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. UKPHR is focused on public safety and believes that a knowledgeable regulator of the entire public health workforce represents the most effective means by which regulation will achieve this purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The public health specialists may be differentiated from most of the other professionals regulated by HCPC because the focus for public health is on population-based interventions. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The knowledge, skills, competences and professional liabilities associated with population-based occupations are very different and, UKPHR would argue, require specialised </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">competence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on the part of the regulator.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Public health specialists who face the prospect of regulation by HCPC might reasonably ask:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Will HCPC expect these leaders in public health to fit in with HCPC’s existing approach to regulation which inevitably, given the large number of registrants, involves more of a “tick box” process?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How will HCPC take account of the role of public health specialists, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carrying responsibility at a strategic level for protecting and enhancing the public's health, in differentiating an existing approach based largely on the regulation of practitioners who work individually with clients?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(c) When will HCPC commence consultation with UKPHR in particular and the wider public health community as a whole to address the many complex issues that will arise on a change of regulator?</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR is committed to introducing a requirement for revalidation for registrants who are public health specialists. Currently, HCPC does not operate a system of revalidation but states that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The HCPC already has robust systems in place to ensure the continuing fitness to practise of our registrants. These include our registration renewals process, continuing professional development standards and fitness to practise processes”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR supports dual registration. Doctors and dentists may register notwithstanding that they are also regulated by the General Medical Council and General Dental Council respectively. Individual doctors and dentists register with UKPHR even though there is no obligation to do so. They register because they feel it is important to keep up their public health-specific expertise and their public health-specific continuing professional development. In due course they will seek revalidation on the same basis. UKPHR has Memoranda of Understanding with the General Medical Council and the General Dental Council governing the regulation of these dually registered individuals – for example who has the lead responsibility in connection with responding to complaints touching on fitness to practise. Currently, the number of doctors and dentists registered is low. However, the issue of dual registration affects larger numbers of UKPHR registrants who are also registered with the Nursing and Midwifery Council, General Pharmaceutical Council and Chartered Institute of Environmental Health. This clearly demonstrates the multi-disciplinary nature of public health leadership. HCPC does not operate dual registration, so in respect of public health specialists it would compel many to choose between two relevant professions and potentially fragment the public health leadership cadre.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR declares an interest in these matters as the existing voluntary regulator.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR is willing to provide further comment and evidence in support and is willing to contribute oral evidence to the Committee if requested.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="line-height:16pt; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Review of the Regulation of Public Health Professionals published in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">November 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Healthy Lives, Healthy People: A Public Health Workforce Strategy </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/healthy-lives-healthy-people-a-public-workforce-strategy"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/healthy-lives-healthy-people-a-public-workforce-strategy</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>